6":"1266","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1265":"omkring 1265","after 1266":"efter 1266","1208":"1208","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England","England":"England","Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Thorpe, Norfolk, England"},"nl":{"1244–1304":"1244–1304","–1266":"–1266","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1285–1339":"1285–1339","–Male":"Overleden","1265–1317":"1265–1317","1208–Male":"1208–Overleden","1210–Female":"1210–Overleden","about 1260":"circa 1260","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1244":"1244","1233":"1233","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1265":"circa 1265","after 1266":"na 1266","1208":"1208","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England","England":"England","Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Thorpe, Norfolk, England"},"en":{"1244–1304":"1244–1304","–1266":"–1266","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1285–1339":"1285–1339","–Male":"Deceased","1265–1317":"1265–1317","1208–Male":"1208–Deceased","1210–Female":"1210–Deceased","about 1260":"about 1260","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1244":"1244","1233":"1233","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1265":"about 1265","after 1266":"after 1266","1208":"1208","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England","England":"England","Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Thorpe, Norfolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Wake","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","occupational name for ‘(man of) the watch’, from Middle English <i>wak</i>, <i>wake</i> ‘wake, vigil, watch, period of guard duty’ (Old English <i>wacu</i>, Old Norse <i>vaka</i>). It alternates with the synonymous Middle English <i>wache</i> (Old English <i>wacce</i>), hence the variant <b>Watch</b>. The surname was also interchangeable with   Waite   (the equivalent Old French term) which, like <i>Wake</i>, was sometimes translated as Latin <i>vigil</i> ‘(one who is) watchful, alert’. Compare the synonymous   Vail  . When the bearers had high social status, the surname probably denoted an officer with responsibility for the security of a castle, town, or royal person. Compare   Wakeman  .","variant of   Wack  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vail","meanings":["English: occupational name from Old French <i>de la veille</i> ‘of the watch, watchman’, with loss of <i>de</i>; compare   Wake  . There has been some confusion with the topographic name   Vale   and the nickname   Veal  .","Scottish: shortened and altered form of   McPhail  , Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Phàil</b> ‘son of Paul’.","Irish: variant of   Veale  ."]},{"name":"Waite","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): occupational name for a watchman, either in a town or castle, from Anglo-Norman French <i>waite</i> ‘watchman, member of the watch’ (of ancient Germanic origin; compare   Wachter  ). In the Middle Ages the town waits typically combined the functions of watchmen and musicians through being trumpeters or pipers. There may also have been some late confusion with   White   or   Wheat  ."]}]},{"name":"Emma","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, originally a short form of compound names such as   Ermintrude   containing the word <i>erm(en)</i>, <i>irm(en)</i> ‘entire’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, but its popularity in medieval England was greatly enhanced by the fact that it had been borne by the mother of Edward the Confessor, herself a Norman. In modern times, it was only in moderate use early in the 20th century but rose sharply in favour in the 1970s and has since remained perennially popular."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Or","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."],"variants":[{"name":"Thor","meanings":["Originally the name of the god of thunder in Norse mythology, Thor (Old Norse <i>Þórr</i>). It was not used as a personal name during the Middle Ages. The modern name is either a late 18th-century revival of the god's name or else a vernacular development of   Tord ."]}]},{"name":"Eleanor","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ellenor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor  , the result of blending with   Ellen ."]},{"name":"Elenor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]},{"name":"Elinor","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Eleanor ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":15,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705190,"age":46,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Emma Or Eleanor Wake was born in 1244, in Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England, her father, Sir Andrew le Wake of Bingham's Melcombe, was 37 and her mother, Jane Porter, was 34. She married Robert Bingham about 1260, in Thorpe, Norfolk, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1304, in England, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1244–1304":"1244–1304","–1266":"–1266","1230–1304":"1230–1304","1285–1339":"1285–1339","–Male":"Surnud","1265–1317":"1265–1317","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1210–Female":"1210–Surnud","about 1260":"umbes 1260","1285":"1285","1230":"1230","1290":"1290","1304":"1304","1259":"1259","1244":"1244","1233":"1233","1266":"1266","1210":"1210","1265":"1265","about 1265":"umbes 1265","after 1266":"pärast 1266","1208":"1208","1339":"1339","1317":"1317","Bingham, Nottinghamshire, England":"Bingham, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England":"Melcombe Horsey, Dorset, England","England":"England","Thorpe, Norfolk, England":"Thorpe, Norfolk, England"},"fi":{"1244–1304":"1244–1304","–1266":"